title: Capital allowances when you sell an asset

heading_context: Capital allowances when you sell an asset
chunks.html_content: When you sell or ‘dispose of’ something you claimed capital allowances on, include the value in your calculations for the accounting period you sell it in.
chunks.plain_content:
Capital allowances when you sell an asset
When you sell or ‘dispose of’ something you claimed capital allowances on, include the value in your calculations for the accounting period you sell it in.

heading_context: Capital allowances when you sell an asset
chunks.html_content: You do not need to do this if you give it to a charity or community amateur sports club (CASC).
chunks.plain_content:

heading_context: Capital allowances when you sell an asset
Dispose of an asset
chunks.html_content:
You dispose of an asset if you:

  • sell it
  • give it away as a gift or transfer it to someone else
  • swap it for something else
  • get compensation for it - like an insurance payout if it’s been lost or destroyed
  • use it for anything other than your business
  • close your business

heading_context: Capital allowances when you sell an asset
Work out the value
chunks.html_content:
The value is usually how much you sold it for.

Use the market value (the amount you’d expect to sell it for) if you:

  • gave it away
  • kept it to use for something other than your business
  • sold it for less than it was worth to someone who’s unable to claim allowances

heading_context: Capital allowances when you sell an asset
If you originally claimed 100% of the item
If you have a balance in the pool your item qualifies for
chunks.html_content:
Add the full value to your profits in your tax return if both of the following apply:

  • you originally claimed 100% of the item under annual investment allowance (AIA) or first year allowances
  • you have nothing in the pool your item qualifies for

This is known as a ‘balancing charge’.

Deduct the full value from that pool if you originally claimed 100% of the item and you have a balance in the pool your item qualifies for.

Add the difference to your profits in your tax return if the value of the item is more than the amount in your pool. This is a ‘balancing charge’.

If there’s a balance left in your pool, you can claim writing down allowances on it.

heading_context: Capital allowances when you sell an asset
If you originally used writing down allowances
chunks.html_content:
If you used writing down allowances when you bought an item, deduct the value from the pool you originally added it to.

Use the amount that’s left to work out your next writing down allowances.

For items in single asset pools, claim any amount that’s left as a capital allowance. Do this in your tax return. The leftover amount is known as a ‘balancing allowance’.

If the value you deduct is more than the balance in the pool, add the difference to your profit. This is a balancing charge.

heading_context: Capital allowances when you sell an asset
If you originally used writing down allowances
chunks.html_content: You can only get a balancing allowance in your main or special rate pool when you close your business. You can get a balancing charge in any pool in any year.
chunks.plain_content:
Capital allowances when you sell an asset
If you originally used writing down allowances
You can only get a balancing allowance in your main or special rate pool when you close your business. You can get a balancing charge in any pool in any year.

heading_context: Capital allowances when you sell an asset
If you sell it for more than it cost you
Connected people
chunks.html_content:
You can only deduct the original cost of the item even if you sell it for more.

If a connected person sold it to you for less than it cost them, deduct either how much you sell it for or how much it cost them - whichever’s smaller.

Add the difference to your profits in your tax return if the value of the item is more than the amount in your pool. This is a balancing charge.

Connected people include your:

  • husband, wife or civil partner and their relatives
  • relatives and their husbands, wives or civil partners
  • business partners and their husbands, wives, civil partners and relatives

Your company is connected with another company if you:

  • control them both
  • are connected with a person who controls the other company
  • are part of a group that controls both companies

heading_context: Capital allowances when you sell an asset
If you close your business
chunks.html_content: In the year you close your business, enter a balancing charge or a balancing allowance on your tax return instead of claiming capital allowances.
chunks.plain_content:
Capital allowances when you sell an asset
If you close your business
In the year you close your business, enter a balancing charge or a balancing allowance on your tax return instead of claiming capital allowances.
